    pearls: ["Glasgow-Blatchford Score of 0-1 identifies very low-risk patients who may be safely discharged for outpatient EGD; this avoids unnecessary hospitalization for low-risk UGIB","Initial hemoglobin may be NORMAL in acute hemorrhage because whole blood is lost proportionally; hemodilution reveals true blood loss over 24-72 hours - do not be falsely reassured by normal Hgb in a tachycardic patient","Coffee-ground emesis does NOT mean bleeding has stopped; it means blood has been exposed to gastric acid and may indicate ongoing hemorrhage","BUN-to-creatinine ratio >20:1 supports UGIB because digested blood protein is absorbed and converted to urea in the proximal GI tract","Hematochezia in a hemodynamically unstable patient should be assumed UGIB until proven otherwise by EGD; brisk upper bleeding can transit rapidly without conversion to melena","In variceal bleeding, prophylactic antibiotics (ceftriaxone) reduce mortality by 20% by preventing spontaneous bacterial peritonitis - this is not optional","Two large-bore (16-18G) peripheral IVs deliver fluid faster than a triple-lumen central line; flow rate is proportional to the fourth power of the catheter radius (Poiseuille's law)","Restrictive transfusion strategy (Hgb threshold 7 g/dL) is associated with better outcomes than liberal transfusion in UGIB, including in variceal bleeding where over-transfusion can increase portal pressure"],
