    pearls: ["C. difficile testing should only be performed on unformed (liquid or soft) stool; never test formed stool or perform test of cure - PCR can remain positive for weeks after successful treatment","Fidaxomicin is now preferred over vancomycin for initial C. difficile episodes due to lower recurrence rates; metronidazole is no longer first-line for any C. difficile episode","E. coli O157:H7 with bloody diarrhea: absolutely NO antibiotics and NO anti-motility agents (loperamide); both increase the risk of developing HUS; supportive IV hydration is the cornerstone of management","Salmonella gastroenteritis in immunocompetent adults is self-limited and does NOT require antibiotics; antibiotics are indicated only for bacteremia, extremes of age, immunosuppression, or prosthetic implants","Fecal microbiota transplantation (FMT) is recommended after 3 or more C. difficile recurrences; FDA-approved microbiome therapeutics (Rebyota, Vowst) have simplified FMT delivery","Norovirus is the most common cause of gastroenteritis outbreaks; alcohol-based hand sanitizers are ineffective against norovirus - soap and water handwashing and bleach-based surface disinfection are required","Afebrile bloody diarrhea should raise immediate suspicion for E. coli O157:H7, especially after exposure to undercooked ground beef, unpasteurized products, or contaminated produce; order Shiga toxin assay and STEC culture","Always assess C. difficile severity at diagnosis: WBC >15,000 or creatinine ≥1.5 defines severe disease and changes the treatment approach"],
