    pearls: ["Treat-to-target urate <6 mg/dL is the cornerstone of gout management; this target is below the saturation point (6.8 mg/dL) ensuring net crystal dissolution over time; <5 mg/dL target for severe tophaceous gout accelerates tophus resolution","HLA-B*5801 screening before allopurinol is MANDATORY in Southeast Asian, African American, and Korean patients; this allele is present in 6-8% of these populations and is strongly associated with fatal allopurinol hypersensitivity (DRESS/SJS/TEN)","Start allopurinol LOW (100 mg/day, 50 mg if CKD ≥3) and titrate SLOWLY to target; the old practice of dose-capping based on creatinine clearance has been abandoned as it leads to subtherapeutic dosing in most patients","Febuxostat carries an FDA boxed warning from the CARES trial showing higher cardiovascular death compared to allopurinol; reserve for patients who fail or cannot tolerate allopurinol, especially those without established cardiovascular disease","NEVER stop or adjust ULT during an acute gout flare; fluctuations in serum urate (up or down) can trigger or prolong flares; continue ULT and treat the flare separately","Colchicine prophylaxis during ULT initiation prevents mobilization flares; continue for at least 3-6 months or until target urate has been maintained for 6 months; the AGREE trial established that low-dose colchicine (1.2 mg + 0.6 mg) is equally effective and far better tolerated than high-dose regimens","Pegloticase requires G6PD screening before initiation; hydrogen peroxide generated during uric acid conversion causes severe hemolysis in G6PD-deficient patients","Serum urate levels can be paradoxically NORMAL during acute gout flares due to the acute phase response and increased renal excretion; never rule out gout based on a normal urate during an acute attack"],
